  "prompt": "How long can a human being survive without sleep?",
  "response": "The exact amount of time a human can survive without sleep is not definitively known, and it varies from person to person. However, the longest scientifically documented case of a person going without sleep is approximately **11 days** (264 hours), achieved by Randy Gardner in 1965 as part of a high school science experiment. During this period, Gardner experienced severe cognitive and physical impairments, including hallucinations, memory lapses, mood swings, and difficulty concentrating.\n\nWhile this case is extreme, most people begin to experience significant negative effects after just **24\u201348 hours** without sleep. These effects include irritability, impaired judgment, slowed reaction times, and difficulty with memory and focus. Prolonged sleep deprivation can lead to more severe consequences, such as **microsleeps** (brief, involuntary episodes of unconsciousness), immune system suppression, and increased risk of accidents or injuries.\n\nIn extreme cases, chronic sleep deprivation can be life-threatening. Animal studies have shown that prolonged sleep deprivation leads to organ failure and death, though the exact mechanism in humans is not fully understood. For most people, **72 hours** without sleep is the point where cognitive and physical functioning becomes severely compromised.\n\nIn summary, while short-term sleep deprivation is not immediately fatal, it is highly detrimental to health and functioning. Regularly getting adequate sleep (typically **7\u20139 hours per night** for adults) is essential for physical, mental, and emotional well-being.",
